    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so you mentioned satellite cells and signaling... it's hard to visualize. is there a way to think about how those cells actually move to the site of the damage? like, what's the \"mechanism\" of them actually finding the torn fibers and fixing them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Think of satellite cells as dormant muscle stem cells located right on the surface of the muscle fiber. When mechanical damage occurs, chemical signals are released from the injured fiber, essentially creating a beacon that attracts these quiescent cells. These cells then activate, proliferate, and differentiate, fusing with the damaged fiber to donate their nuclei, allowing the muscle to synthesize more contractile proteins and grow bigger.",
